@ENDNODE
@NODE reqs "RamSnap Requirements"

@{jcenter}R E Q U I R E M E N T S
@{jleft}

*  RamSnap requires that you have an Amiga running OS2.0 (I think) or above.
   It may or may not work on anything earlier. But then who cares?

*  MagicWorkbench. Errm, it doesn't exactly require this, but it does require the line
   that MWB inserts into your user-startup sequence.
   
   ie "copy > NIL: SYS:S/RAM.info TO RAM:Disk.info"
   
   If this line isn't there, RamSnap will dutifully snap the Ram Disk Icon, but your
   computer won't remember at startup!

   The Install Script will NOT insert this line into your user-startup script. Sorry.
        
*  ps. A hard disk is always useful  ;-)

@ENDNODE
@NODE notes "RamSnap Notes"

@{jcenter}N O T E S

@{jleft}

RamSnap was written using DevPac 3.14, and the trusty "ed" editor (guide file editing) and
the Includes & Autodocs. (If you don't have the Amiga Developers CD, get it now!)

However, RamSnap isn't perfect....

* RamSnap doesn't bother checking whether it is already running or not.
  There shouldn't be a problem if more than one is running at once though, and I've tested
  up to about 8 at once. So there.

* It doesn't care about alternative places to store the Ram Disk Icon. see @{"Requirements" Link requirements)

* You cannot quit RamSnap. (And I wouldn't terminate the task using ARTM either).
        
* There are few useful error messages. Suffice to say, if there is a problem it will
  simply not run. ie. If you do not have dos.library v36 or above, the program will just
  fail.

* The executable could be optimised to be about 60 bytes smaller. Big Deal.

* No 68020/030/040/060 Optimised versions? For a program this size, you must be joking!


@ENDNODE
@NODE Author "RamSnap Author"

@{jcenter}T H E   A U T H O R
@{jleft}

RamSnap was written by Nick Ryan

        
It took me at least a morning and a half to write this utility, and that included
learning how to write an Installer script and then figuring out the basics of writing
an AmigaGuide document. My biggest problem was figuring out that the DevPac editor
saves text in a way which MultiView/AmigaGuide doesn't like!
        
        
I am contactable via E-Mail at "avatar@patrol.i-way.co.uk"

@ENDNODE
